6. Quod timide dicam. Classen remarks—⁴ Haec non modestiae ’ oeusa, ut Sylvius interpretatur, Cicero adiecit, sed quod, in tam turpi . causa, vix honestum videbatur tantum a se esse praestitum! This view appears to me altogether erroneous. Roman pleaders frequently refused ’ to undertake the defence of a disreputable client; but when a pleader had once undertaken a cause, it was held by all that he was bound to do his best for it, whether good or bad. But Cicero goes farther: he jd not only says that he actually did his best, but he implies that he made such exertions that no one could think (⁶ if he might say so without - presumption') that the advocate had failed to make the most of the cause.
